# glance

Section 1:
What does it do:
`glance` reads a file and prints a quick summary: the first 5 lines and the last 5 lines all in a single command. It's meant to save time compared to running `head`, `tail`, and `wc` separately when you just want a fast overview of a file's contents.

How to run it:
You would run it with "node newfile.js <filename>"

Command Combinations:
This is a easy-to-use command which combines 'head', 'tail', and 'wc' into a single summary command.


Section 2:
what you asked AI:
I asked AI to help explain to me the other commands such as "cat", "wc", etc because I was not fully aware. 


where AI helped:
Giving examples of the various commands in actual uses. 


where you had to think independently:
I did so when having to write the glance code myself like when using split and join commands. 


what AI got wrong or missed:
The start of troubleshooting relied on me correctly describing what happened, so a few rounds of back-and-forth were necessary before the actual bug (like the `git branch add origin` vs `git remote add origin` typo) was recognized. 
